description:
Bishop Isaiah Reed is coming to Innovative Sessions to share his amazing story on how God changed his life! You don't want to miss this!

If you are a musician, artist, or just someone who wants to showcase your talents, then come check us at Goody Goody Bar and Grill!

We are currently taking sign ups for performers! You can reserve your spot to perform by filling out this form:
http://goo.gl/forms/4LPvHMinnJuxC14K3.

Innovative Sessions is a place where local artists can showcase their talents. We invite you to join us at Goody Goody Bar and Grill for an hour long Church service starting at 7pm followed up by live entertainment from all genres at 8pm. Please help us spread the word so we can create a dynamic community at Innovative Sessions.

Church service from 7:00 - 8:00pm

Live entertainment from 8:00 - 10:00pm

If you aren't a musician or artist but love art and music please come, hang out and enjoy the show!

Goody Goody Bar and Grill

(1272 S King St, Honolulu, HI 96814)

Street parking available. Parking also available in back of Goody Goody.

Additional Parking available at the Interstate Building parking structure. Cost is $3.

(1314 S King St, Honolulu, HI 96814)

If you have questions, comments or concerns, please email us [masked].

description:
What will be we doing?


Bring your art materials, ideas and passion, and join us for another of our regular practical creative art-making session.Â 

Who can join?Â 
If you live anywhere in Greater Manchester and are looking for a group to join, look no further, you are welcome at Ancoats Visual Arts. Â 


If you're looking for a regular creative art group to get involved with - then this could be the place for you. Â Remember, it's up to you what you do each week, so get your thinking caps on - I look forward to seeing the results over the weeks that follow.


Does it cost to attend?
Yes.
Reserve your place by clicking RSVP. Â 
Â£4 payable in cash on the day.
Tea, coffee available by donation.

REMEMBER
Click RSVPÂ if you would like to attend this session.Â 
UN-click RSVP if you change your mind and are unable to attend.

Where: Pollard Street, M4 7JA. Click here for directions.
Access to the studio: When you arrive at Hope Mill contact the 'Gallery studio' phone on [masked] and one of the group will let you in.

Is this your first time? All new members will be asked to agree to some basic ground rules by signing the 'Group Rules'.

REMEMBER
Click RSVP if you would like to attend this session.


DirectionsÂ 
Click here for details - you know you want to!Â 
Hope Mill has a lift and heating, and is easy to get to by bus, Metrolink, car, bike or foot.

Is this group for me?
Beginners, intermediate and experienced artists of all ages (18 years +) are welcome - even if you've never done art before but want to start - enthusiasm is all you need.

The studio is fully equipped so all you'll need are art materials and a willingness to give things a go.

description:
Come along on WednesdayÂ 14thÂ DecemberÂ to see an exhibition at the RoyalÂ College of PhysiciansÂ about the Great Fire of London.
Â  About the exhibition
The 1666 Great Fire of London was a final calamity forÂ a city weakened by more than three decades of destruction.

Discover the fascinating story of the razing and rebuilding of the RoyalÂ College of Physicians in the heart of the cityÂ after the firestorm engulfed it.

TheÂ exhibition follows the story of London's 17th centuryÂ physiciansÂ as they were divided by war, battled with plague and almost ruined by flames, only to emerge withÂ a magnificent new home designed by Robert Hooke.

The visit should last aboutÂ 1h 10mins and is guided by the curator of the exhibition.Â Â 

The guided tourÂ isÂ Â£7 per person (payable on the day).

Afterwards we will head to the 'Green Man pub'Â 81 Euston RoadÂ a short walk from theÂ station for a chat over a drink.

Please note, we only waitÂ outside the station for 10 minutes after the advertised meeting time, so please be early or on time.

If you can't see us outside the station, please text.

Look out for the group sign:

Hope to see you there!

Robert

IMPORTANT! You need key pad code to get into Essex Studios. Call me @[masked] if you are coming to class for first time.


ADULT BEGINNERS - "begin from the beginning". Or, more advanced students - start where you "left off". Bring your sketch book or sketch pad or if you are doing watercolor, buy a watercolor "block", some drawing pencils, eraser, brushes, a set of watercolors. I have some supplies for sale, too. Save $$.


On going - start any time. "Pay as you go". Classes startÂ "anytime" betweenÂ 3:10 pmÂ - $5.00 an hr. or $10 for a 2 hr. session. We're done at 7 pm at the latest. Call Karen [masked] to get into front door of Essex Studios. Parking in front lot off Essex Place (runs between McMillan & Wm. Howard Taft).

Shop @ Plaza, Michaels, Suders for art supplies or check out some on-line stores such as Cheap Joe's. For books go to Amazon & eBay, Half Price Books, and Ohio Book Store or visit your local library.

description:
Come along on Wednesday 14th December for a Candlelight Christmas Carol Concert at the church of St Stephen Walbrook in the City!

About the church
The church of St Stephen Walbrook was Sir Christopher Wren's parish church, he lived about 100 metres away.Â  Wren rebuilt the church after its medieval predecessorÂ was destroyed in the Great Fire of London in 1666.Â Â It opened in 1687Â with a dome, which wasÂ used as a prototype for the dome of St Paul's Cathedral, which he started building a few years later.

The church was also whereÂ The Samaritans charity was started in 1953 by vicar Chad Varah using just one phone (which you can see in the church today).Â  It also has a centre altar, which is unusual in English churches.

The concert will last about 1h 30mins.

The carol concertÂ is free!

After the concert,Â they offer free mulled wine and minced piesÂ in the church.

If you arrive later than 5:45pm, come into the church and find a seat and lookout for the group at the end.Â  The concert starts at 6pm.

Lookout for the group sign outside the church:

Look forward to seeing you there.

Robert

description:
Woo Hoo!! Moonrise is at 5:58, so we will have a beautiful moonlit walk! We will need flashlights only for a couple areas that are beneath the trees. This is a nice easy 60- to 65-minute walk on pavement and soft-surface trails. Bring layers, hat, gloves, and a flashlight. It can get chilly down by the creek. We'll start walking at 6:05 sharp.

Suitable for beginners who can keep a good pace. We'll follow the sidewalk several blocks to the park entrance, cross at the light, and pass the duck pond. We'll wander on some flat, open trails and return to our cars at about 7:10. No hill climbing in the dark.

Meet in the big parking lot at the intersection of Melrose and Shadow Ridge and not at the parking lot near the duck pond. The parking lot is adjacent to a ball field and DOES NOT have a gate. Look for a 2002 pewter-colored Prius. Rest rooms are now available in the park, by the duck pond.

Cross-posted with Hiking Addicts. This event repeats every Wednesday.

The "Second Wednesday Costumed/Long Pose Workshop" will be held every second Wednesday of each month. It will be ONE pose with a strong emphasis on the composition, and the model will be costumed. The model may be standing, seated, or reclining, and the composition may include props as well.
Of course you are welcome to paint and/or draw, and any medium is welcome but please be considerate of others when using oils and solvents (meaning odorless and non-toxic please).
The workshops are $15 per 3-hour session. You may pay in advance online or at the door (cash and PayPal accepted). Please check our calendar for schedule and workshop/class descriptions . . . and of course ALL levels are welcome!
Please visit www.studio1021.com for more information.
Thank you and see you soon!

description:
More on where and when to meet coming shortly:

Enjoy an evening of art and activities celebrating Hanukkah.Â 

Free admission begins at 4 pm.Â 
All events areÂ free.

Welcome to an evening of art, culture, and community. Enjoy festive performances, view artistsâ€™ installations, and participate in a one-of-a-kind virtual reality experience. Make art, tour the galleries, and learn about the MFAâ€™s collection of Judaica to celebrate Hanukkah, the festival of lightsâ€”bringing the miracle, illumination, and innovation of Hanukkah toÂ Boston.

SpecialÂ Events


Welcome and Community Candle LightingÂ 
6:30 pm | Shapiro Family CourtyardÂ 
Join Ann and Graham Gund Director Matthew Teitelbaum for welcome remarks. Matan Zamir, Deputy Consul General of Israel to New England; Neil Wallack, chair, CJP Board of Directors; Rabbi Elaine Zecher of Temple Israel; Jamie Lis Tarlow, chair, MFA Board of Trustees; Susie Tanchel, head of school, Jewish Community Day School; Rabbi Jillian Cameron, director, InterfaithFamily/Boston; Jamie Darsa, coordinator, PJ Library; and Laura Conrad Mandel, executive director of the Jewish Arts Collaborative, offer a community blessing and illuminate a large-scale, one-of-a-kind menorah. The United Stated Postal Service also unveils its 2016 HanukkahÂ stamp.

Menorah Installation:Â Step to Hanukkah LightsÂ 
5â€“10 pm | Shapiro Family CourtyardÂ 
Nine freestanding candle-like branches of the menorah emerge from a custom platform. The platform invites guests to step up and down to the menorahâ€™s branches, each topped with a beautiful â€œflameâ€ù created from light that changes in response to viewers. Created by Andrew Ringler, creative technologist and educator; Fish McGill, Boston-based drawer, designer, and educator; and Saul Baizman, dynamic media designer, software developer, and designÂ educator.

A Mixed Reality Short Performance:Â InworldsÂ 
5:45, 7:15, and 8:15 pm Level G, Alfond AuditoriumÂ 
Join us for a story of loss, miracles, friendship, and discovery, inspired by the themes of Hanukkah. This experimental performance features interaction between a live actor and a volunteer immersed in virtual reality. Through a new â€œmixed realityâ€ù storytelling medium, the production bathes the entire stage in projected visuals, taking the audience on a 15-minute journey through fantastical worlds. Avital Manor-Pelegâ€™s improvisational masked performance is a first-of-its-kind exploration in how virtual reality transforms participants into performers. Created and presented by Secret Portal in association with Dudley SquareÂ Studios.

Free tickets are available at the Alfond Auditorium ticket desk 30 minutes before show times. First come, first served; limited availability. Free ticket required forÂ entry.

Music Hanukkah Song and Story TimeÂ 
5â€“6 pm | Education Center in Druker Family Pavilion, Room 160Â 
Join PJ Library for Hanukkah singing and an interactive reading ofSadieâ€™s Almost Marvelous MenorahÂ and other stories. Stephen Brickman, founder of the Sing-Together Project, leads theÂ singing.

Sing Along with Becky KhitrikÂ 
7:15â€“7:35 pm | Shapiro Family CourtyardÂ 
7:50â€“8:10, and 8:25â€“8:45 pm | Gallery G86Â 
Join cantor, educator, klezmer clarinetist, and musical community builder, Becky Khitrik to and sing along with favorite songs about Hanukkah, faith, andÂ freedom.

Dance: Wendy JehlenÂ 
7â€“7:20, 7:40â€“8, and 8:15â€“8:35 pm Gallery 332Â 
Wendy Jehlen, founder and artistic director of Anikaya Dance, weaves together music, dance, and storytelling from disparate traditions and different ways ofÂ understanding.

Ezekielâ€™s Wheels Klezmer BandÂ 
7â€“7:30, 7:45â€“8:15, and 8:30â€“9 pm Shapiro Family CourtyardÂ 
Boston-based Ezekielâ€™s Wheels is an internationally recognized klezmer ensemble whose joyfully contagious energy creates a fun contemporary perspective on traditional JewishÂ music.

Nigun Chamber EnsembleÂ 
7:20â€“7:40, 7:55â€“8:15, and 8:30â€“8:50 pm Gallery 168Â 
The award-winning Nigun Chamber Ensemble (nigunÂ means melody in Hebrew) preserves the unique musical heritage of Jewish composers and their communities in pre-war Eastern Europe. Featuring Sargis Karapetyan, violin; Valerie Shleppi, soprano; Yelena Neplok, artistic director, piano; Chester Brezniak, clarinet; Cynthia Forbes,Â cello.

Art-MakingÂ Activities DreidelsÂ 
5â€“9 pm | Education Center in Druker Family Pavilion, Room 159Â 
Dreidel, dreidel, dreidelâ€_create your own clay dreidel with local artist Tova Speter, founder of The MEM Project. Be inspired by the designs you see around theÂ Museum.

Menorah MakingÂ 
5â€“9 pm | Shapiro Family CourtyardÂ 
Visit the large-scale interactive menorah for inspiration as you celebrate the light of Hanukkah and create your ownÂ menorah.

Drawing in the GalleriesÂ 
6â€“9 pm | Gallery 271Â 
Get drawing tips and ideas from an artist as you sketch in theÂ galleries.

Tours andÂ Talks Panel: Judaica and Judaism in BostonÂ 
7:30â€“8:30 pm | Remis AuditoriumÂ 
Join Marietta Cambareri, Senior Curator of European Sculpture and Jetskalina H. Phillips Curator of Judaica; Rabbi Jillian Cameron, director, InterfaithFamily/Boston; Barnet Kessel, executive director, Vilna Shul; and Silvina Mizrahi, artist and educator, for an engaging and informative discussion about the MFAâ€™s collection of Judaica, Judaism in Boston and beyond, and much more. Panel is oneÂ hour.

Free lecture tickets are available at Remis Auditorium Box Office 30 minutes before show time. First come, first served; limited availability. Free lecture ticket required forÂ entry.

Spotlight Talks: JudaicaÂ 
6, 7, 7:30, and 8 pm | Level 1, Galleries 127 and 142; Level 2, Gallery 258; and Level 3, Gallery 336Â 
Drop in to enjoy an exploration of works of art in the MFAâ€™s collection of Judaica. Visit any of the galleries listed, at any of the times listed, for one of these 15-minuteÂ talks.

American Sign Language TourÂ 
6 pm | Meet at Sharf Visitor CenterÂ 
Join Dan Peters to learn about works of Judaica in the MFAâ€™s collection. No spoken EnglishÂ translation.

Judaica in the GalleriesÂ 
Objects of Judaica are located in several galleries around the Museum; visit the following locations to further explore Jewish art and culture. Level 1, Galleries 127 and 142; Level 2, Gallery 258; and Level 3, GalleryÂ 336

Above: Image courtesy of Pravin Pant, ImpravÂ Images

description:
Let's do an appetizer â€œnibblesâ€ù potluck this year, at Stellar Studios.
I want to invite all of you to come see the "New" Stellar Studios. Those of you who have been here before will be amazed at the transformation, and if you haven't been here, Welcome!
First priority; Food
Ideas: Chips n dip
cheese n crackers
carrots n florets
gluten free pizza bites / anything
wine or fizzy drinks
I'll provide plates/ cups/ napkins - no forks -
If you're signing up to bring a nibble please add it to your RSVP
If you don't want to, or can't bring anything, (coming from work, ran out of time, etc.)
Don't worry about it! Bring your own self. That's why we're getting together, to see friends we haven't seen for a while or to make new ones. There will always be plenty to eat.

As for the baubles, how about we make them at the potluck? Along with bringing something fun to nibble on, or fun to drink; bring some things to work on. - Only if you want to. See above -
I'll have work space set up if you want to bring some already fused small glass bits, (I have some available) I've found the cutest 1in star ornaments that would be the perfect bail for bright & shiny bits.
Or bring other things that can be glued, wired or otherwise assembled, bring it! - And maybe some to share. -
Let's eat, visit, tour, and plan for 2017, you know it will be fun.
December, It's here! (How did it get here so fast?)

description:
***YOUR FIRST CLASS IS FREE!***

RSVP FEE: $10 (non-refundable) to save your seat in class. (Note: I will refund if class is cancelled, of course.)

â€¢ If this is your FIRST class I will return your $10 to you IN CLASS.

â€¢ If you don't RSVP I cannot guarantee you a seat.

â€¢ Class discount cards: $150 for 15 $10 punches ($30/class) Available in the studio.

â€¢ Walk-in (no card): $35 per class

Cash, check, Stripe, Paypal accepted for class fees and class cards.

Check out galleries of student work here and Susie's work here.

***************Unfold Your Creative Spirit Studio is a magical space, and I'm your guide, artist Susie Stonefield Miller. I've created a feeling of gentle safety and openness in my creative haven. This is not just an art class. It's women's community. It's healing and transformation. And it's habit-forming!

Art journaling is a NO RULES explorative and playful creative practice. You don't need to be "artistic" to find your Inner Artist.

Did you know that awakening your creative spirit opens all sorts of doors in other aspects of your life? Creativity, productivity, emotional clarity, dreams...all of this and more!

***************

Bring a sketchbook (or buy one in class for $18-29) and begin your art journaling journey!

All the materials are there, you don't need to clear a space to find yourself! Journaling prompts provided, technique and skills demos frequently provided.

Explore, create, spill your heart. Connect with other women*. Relax into this magical, creative space and take care of YOU.

Aprons, tea, and soothing music are provided too. What are you waiting for?

***************

Enfin, au troisiÃ¨me trimestre, nous travaillerons deÂ maniÃ¨re encore plusÂ rapide et variÃ©e, enÂ dÃ©veloppant un univers plus personnel. Le dessin dâ€™observation pourra se faire plus onirique, imaginaire, libre et parfois moins rÃ©aliste si cela favorise une vrai direction de travail.

description:
*This End-of-Year Meetup features a costumed model as a Christmas Elf!

Been meaning to draw more? And meet great people too?Â 

Do both! Come relax and learn with us at The Artists Showplace!

We welcome people who have a love of art, who want to meet new people, who want to learn from other artists, who want to start drawing but classes are too expensive, who draw all the time or haven't drawn for years (or ever!).Â 

It only costs $20 to participate, which pays for the model, the workspace, and the extended gallery hours.Â 

The main purpose of these meetups is to provide a wide variety of figure drawing opportunities. Life drawing is a drawing of the human from observation of a live model. Many artists consider this form of study to be the most effective way to sharpen artist skills. We have people of all ranges in experience, from the complete beginner to the very experienced.

It is very important to have the perfect atmosphere to create a drawing state of mind. That is why our sessions take place in our eclectic gallery, a fixture of the north Dallas art scene for nearly two decades, with an appropriate selection of music that brings a creative flow to our participants. What makes our Meetups different? We like to share our work and hangout to talk and admire art. Share tips and learn from people in a casual environment that is friendly and non-judgmental! All levels of artists are very welcome!

Absolutely no experience is necessary, just a desire to explore your creative side! Our aim is to provide a warm, supportive and inspirational environment for all who want to join.

We hope to see you soon!

Suggested Supplies ListÂ 

GET A 20% DISCOUNT AT ASEL ART SUPPLIES! Mention that you are a student at The Artists Showplace to get 20% off of your purchase at checkout.Â 

- Paper: Strathmore is a common, quality brand found in places like Hobby Lobby, Michaels, and Joanne's. There are special kinds of paper for watercolor or pastels, so keep and eye out based on what medium you are using.Â 

-Pencils: For life drawing, working loosely tends to be more effective for the time allotted than taking a tight and detailed approached. An Ebony Graphite pencil from a reliable brand like Prismacolor is effective for a loose approach. A Pentel mechanical pencil is effective for a tight, detailed but more time consuming approach.Â

description:
Greetings Everyone!Â Can you believe?Â  Only 3 workshops left in 2016!Â  At this weekâ€™s workshop, all of the warm-ups, exercises and games will be by random selection randomly selected by randomly-selected participants.Â  We have played quite a few games over the past 2 years so there will be a lot of suggestions from which to choose.Â 

As many of you know, there is a high priority placed on laughter at each and every workshop.Â  There are aÂ  myriad of bona fide reasons for doing so.Â  In â€œOutsmart Yourself:Â  Brain-Based Strategies to a Better Youâ€ù it states:Â  â€œThere is good evidence that laughter helps keep your brain especially stimulatedâ€_one of the central mechanisms is incongruity detection and then resolution.Â  As your brain identifies incongruityÂ  and then corrects its initial interpretation of the incongruity, it engages a remarkably wide rangeÂ  of brain areas.Â  Language areas become more active when a stimulus is funny.Â  TheÂ  medial prefrontal cortex, posterior cingulate cortex, precuneus, superior temporal gyrus, and superiorÂ  temporal sulcus show similar boosts in activation.Â  Laughter is also associated with a substantial release of dopamine into the pleasure circuits of the brain.â€ùÂ  Wow!!!Â  Thereâ€™s nothing like having your brain showered with dopamine!

But wait!Â  Thereâ€™s more!Â  Here are a few words about dopamine:Â  Taken from the internet, â€œThere are about 86Â billion neurons in the human brain.Â  [These neurons]Â communicate with each other via brain chemicals called neurotransmitters.Â  Dopamine is a neurotransmitter thatâ€™s a key factor in motivation, productivity, and focus.Â  Dopamine has been called our â€œmotivation molecule.â€ùÂ  It boosts ourÂ drive, focus, and concentration.Â  It enables us to plan ahead and resist impulses so we can achieve our goals.Â  It gives us that â€œI did it!â€ù liftÂ when we accomplish what we set out to do.Â  It makes us competitive and provides the thrill of the chase in all aspects of life â€” business, sports, and love.Â  Dopamine is in charge ofÂ our pleasure-reward system.Â  ItÂ allows us to have feelings of enjoyment, bliss, and even euphoria.Â  But tooÂ little dopamine can leave you unfocused,Â unmotivated, lethargic, and even depressed.â€ù

Soâ€_even though we play silly, childlike games and use our childlike imagination at our workshops, the positive benefits that transpire in our brain are beyond significant!Â  All this and more happens each week at our workshops!

This Wednesdayâ€™s Got U Laughing Workshop starts at 7!Â Arrive early to get the Happy Hour prices on your drinks (Happy Hour ends at 7) and/or to eat your food before the workshop starts.Â  Just in case you cannot arrive by 7, you should know that late arrivals are permitted to participate as our door is always open.

NON-PARTICIPATING AUDIENCE MEMBERS WELCOME!Â If you know anyone who does not want to participate but just be a part of the audience, there is no charge for non-participation.Â However, if non-participating, it would be best to arrive before 7 to let me know and audience members will still have to purchase at least one item fromÂ Jungle Billâ€™s because that is the expectation of the restaurant.

PLEASE come to the workshop thirsty/hungry as everyone is expected to purchase at least one item as management keeps track of how many people attend and how many order.Â 

Got U Laughing meets at theÂ JUNGLE BILLS TIKE GRILLÂ located at 2950 Gulf to Bay Boulevard, Clearwater, FLÂ every Wednesday evening fromÂ 7 to 9 PM.Â We meet in an enclosed room for privacy. Â Admission fee is $5; a minimum of 1 item must be purchased from the bar or menu.Â Got U LaughingÂ features clean comedy with the emphasis on spontaneous creativity.Â No prior improv experience is required.

To learn more about the workshop, please go to:Â www.Meetup.com/Got-U-Laughing-Improv-Comedy.


Kim M. Clark - DirectorGot U Laughing Improv - Clearwater[masked] meetup.com/got-U-Laughing-Improv-Comedy For more info, email Kim M. Clark - Director at [masked].

description:
This event is free; no tickets are required. Harvard Book Store welcomes JANE KAMENSKYâ€”Professor of History at Harvard University and author of The Exchange Artistâ€”for a discussion of her latest book, A Revolution in Color: The World of John Singleton Copley.
About A Revolution in Color

Boston in the 1740s: a bustling port at the edge of the British empire. A boy comes of age in a small wooden house along the Long Wharf, which juts into the harbor, as though reaching for London thousands of miles across the ocean. Sometime in his childhood, he learns to draw.

That boy was John Singleton Copley, who became, by the 1760s, colonial Americaâ€™s premier painter. His brush captured the faces of his neighborsâ€”ordinary men like Paul Revere, John Hancock, and Samuel Adamsâ€”who would become the revolutionary heroes of a new United States. Today, in museums across America, Copleyâ€™s brilliant portraits evoke patriotic fervor and rebellious optimism.

The artist, however, did not share his subjectsâ€™ politics. Copleyâ€™s nation was Britain; his capital, London. When rebellion sundered Britainâ€™s empire, both kin and calling determined the painterâ€™s allegiances. He sought the largest canvas for his talents and the safest home for his family. So, by the time the United States declared its independence, Copley and his kin were in London. He painted Americaâ€™s revolution from a far shore, as Britainâ€™s American War.

An intimate portrait of the artist and his extraordinary times, Jane Kamenskyâ€™s A Revolution in Color masterfully reveals the world of the American Revolution, a place in time riven by divided loyalties and tangled sympathies. Much like the world in which he lived, Copleyâ€™s life and career were marked by spectacular rises and devastating falls. But though his ambivalence cost him dearly, the painterâ€™s achievements in both Britain and America made him a towering figure of both nationsâ€™ artistic legacies.

description:
You've probably seen plenty of Youtube videos showing amazing special effects makeup that completely transforms a person look, species, etc. Here's your chance to get an in-person how-to session with experienced makeup artist team Belladonna's Cupboard.

Learn the differences between makeup for theater, film, and live events like haunts, and several techniques from each to create wounds, age people, and in general what works and what doesn't. This is a great class for cosplayers who want to take their cosplay character to the next level.

Participants will each get a starter FX kit with all the supplies necessary to participate in the class and to begin playing and learning after. Class cost: $75/person (all materials included)

This class is open to both Hammerspace members AND non-members, but you must sign up before this class fills up! Outside food and beverages (adult or otherwise) are welcome.

description:
**Garrett Centre Venue,[masked] Mansford St, London E2 6LX**


Bethnal Green London E2 Life Drawing Class:
Nearly 100% of all feedback rates us 5*

The popular, long established Bethnal Green Life Drawing Class taught by Adrian Dutton (www.adriandutton.com) now runs a drop-in classes on Monday, Tuesday,Â Wednesday,Â Thursday and Friday evenings. There's no need to book, we run these classes as drop-in classes, so you can simply come along to this lovely, lively class taught by Adrian in the Garrett Centre, a spacious, lofty space in Bethnal Green, London E2.

We have been getting together for serious drawing work (and the odd drink afterwards!) for 12 years. Newcomers are always welcome! This class suits people of all levels of experience. Adrian has trained with some of the countries leading painters, such as Francis Hoyland, John Lessore, Ann Dowker, Tim Hyman, and others. Adrian's style is hands-on, affirming and very warm and friendly. But it is the atmosphere of the group itself that really makes this drawing class so special. Come along for an evening or email Adrian at [masked] for more information.Â 

The costÂ per class is Â£8.50 per evening (Â£6 concs.) or Â£30 for a block of 5 sessions if you want to prepay.

All materials are available at the class or bring your own.

Â "A benefit showing of The Cherokee Word for Water, followed by a question and answer session with the producers and possibly one of the actors via Skype, will be held at 7 p.m. Thursday, December. 14th, at the Madrona Grace Presbyterian Church/Madrona Commons, in Seattle's Central area (32nd & Marion).

The film tells the story of the work that led Wilma Mankiller to become the first modern female Chief of the Cherokee Nation and is being shown to raise funds for the Water Protectors at the Standing Rock Sioux Reservation. Members of the Standing Rock Sioux have been trying to stop an oil pipeline being constructed by Energy Transfer Partners that runs a short distance from their reservation across lands containing ancestral graves and artifacts.

The pipeline originally was planned for an area closer to Bismarck, ND, but residents there voiced concerns for their drinking water in the event of a pipeline break, so the pipeline was moved south. The Standing Rock Sioux have said that by crossing under the Missouri River, the pipeline will endanger drinking water for their reservation and for others downstream. They are being supported by many other American Indian tribes and nations, as well as by indigenous groups from South America and New Zealand.

There is a suggested donation of between $10 and $50 for those attending, though no one will be turned away. The money raised will be used for the legal defense of the more than 400 water protectors who have been arrested and for supplies for the camps for the coming winter.

According to the film website, â€œThe Cherokee Word For Water was voted the top American Indian film of the past 40 years in a survey conducted by the American Indian Film Institute in 2015. â€œ

The film runs 1 hour and 40 minutes and is appropriate for all audiences."

description:
Unique weekly acting classes in Meisner Technique

Dubbed the technique that works, the Meisner Technique is the most practical method acting technique available to actors seeking career development and personal growth.

We run 2 x weekly foundations classes from our purpose built studio right in the heart of Brick Lane.

We also run short courses, audition workshops and screen acting classes.

The weekly acting classes are a perfect opportunity to challenge yourself and discover your emotional truth. They are provided on a drop in basis.Â 

Each class we work through exercises and tasks designed to progressively get you out of your comfort zone. You can choose to join us as often as you like but attending weekly means quicker progress and the opportunity to meet and connect with other people more consistently.


The classes will be fun, exciting, at times intense and deeply affecting.

All welcome, you don't need to have any acting previous experience. In fact the less experience the better!

What is the Meisner Method:

A technique used by professional actors to enable them to give intense, captivating, truthful performance on stage and film.

Who was Sanford Meisner:

A famous method trained actor and teacher who developed his own technique designed to more practically and effectively elicit powerful and truthful performances.

Many of Hollywood's most famous actors have trained in the Meisner Technique. It is regarded in the industry as 'the technique that works'.

Here is a small list of well known and successful Meisner actors, some of which Meisner himself trained:

Sandra Bullock, David Duchovny, Tina Fey, James Franco, Michelle Pfeiffer, Naomi Watts, Tom Cruise, Alec Baldwin, Jim Carey, Christoph Waltz, James Gandolfini, Jon Voight, Dylan McDermott, Eileen Fulton, James Caan, Steve McQueen, Gregory Peck, Eli Wallach, Diane Keaton, Robert Duvall, Lee Grant, Peter Falk, Jeff Goldblum, Grace Kelly, and Sydney Pollack.

Who would benefit from the classes:

1. Actors interested in pursuing professional career in acting.

2. Almost anyone interested in really discovering and challenging themselves.

Visit our website as well for more info: Actors Door Studio

<a>
</a>

The Classes: Classes at the Actors Door Studio are full on immersive experiences. Each class runs like a 3 hour workshop and is a participatory event.

Be prepared to be challenged!

Meisner is method acting approach to acting. It is designed to be challenging and to put you out of your comfort zone. It is not a 'light' fun and games type of acting technique. (If that is what you after this is not the right class for you!). Visit our site to find out what you can expect from our acting classes.

A little about your instructor: Fay Beck trained in the Meisner Technique in Sydney with teachers who were students of Meisner himself. She graduated top of her class in 2006. Since graduating she taught the craft privately in Sydney before her move to London where she has begun to take the course to the next level. She discovered Meisner during her early undergraduate days whilst studying Psychology at the University of Sydney. She has since developed this weekly programme and created the Actors Door Studio to bring Meisner to would-be professional actors as well as to any individual interested in re-connecting with their instinctive self. She is a filmmaker and writer and has a passion for teaching Meisner.

Payments: For convenience I have enabled Paypal payments for this meetup but I can accept payment via direct bank deposit. You can do that by booking the class on our website: http://www.londonactingclasses.com/courses/drop-in-acting-classes-london-meisner-foundations/. Select 'direct bank transfer' at the checkout and ensure you have the correct amount on the day. You spot will only be confirmed once we receive payment from you. WE DO NOT ACCEPT CASH PAYMENTS.Â 

Please be on time!

description:
Invitation for local Bay Area artists to take part in our ongoing painting workshop:

If youâ€™re looking to grow as an artist, need feedback, or are looking for a new direction, this might be your perfect opportunity. Whether you work with oils, acrylics, watercolors or pastels ... you are welcome to drop in and bring your paints and painting with you, or a blank canvas. The class is instructed but relaxed and self-paced, and we will assist you technically, conceptually and compositionally in every way. Dickson Schneider (the instructor) works with each artist individually and the class has all manner of feedback - from assignments, to conceptual discussions about your direction, to the particulars of the piece you are making.

We meet on a regular basis every Wednesday and Sunday:

Wednesdays from 7-10pm

Sundays from 3-6pm

Cost $20 per 3-hour session

Instructor: Dickson Schneider

Dickson Schneider has taught at California State University East Bay for 15 years, over 25 different classes - Painting, Drawing, Art History and seminars on contemporary art. He is an accomplished artist in many different media, including Oils, Acrylics, and Egg Tempera as well as video and digital art. One of his activities is visiting the art world in person and in the past six years he has been to New York, Miami, Los Angeles, Berlin, Munich, Portland, Seattle (and more) visiting the particular art scenes there. This first hand look at the contemporary art world has enriched and shaped his own work as well as his teaching.Â 

Questions?Â 

Email Dickson Schneider directly at

Newcomers are always welcome. Â We'll either play as one team or split into several teams for the night depending on how many people RSVP.

This is not an event night at Rogers Place, so parking meters are free after 6pm.Â  There's an evening flat rate of $5 at the Edmonton City Centre West Parkade (connecting to the mall).Â  Entrances are on 102 Street (south of 103 Avenue) or 103 Street (east side, between 102 Avenue and 103 Avenue).Â  **On event nights, you can still get a $5 rate there (instead of the $20 special event rate) but you MUST tell the attendant when you enter that you're going to Pubstumpers at Fionn MacCools (save your receipt in case you're asked for proof when you leave)**Â 


Many TheatreGoers have enjoyed this fun pub quiz. Â If you enjoy playing Trivial Pursuit, you'll enjoy this event. Â The quiz has 8 rounds worth a total of 80 points with questions on a wide variety of subjects read by a Quiz Master. Â There is typically something for everyone. Â The first round starts with 10 general knowledge questions worth 1 point each, a music round with 10 snippets of songs requiring the name of the song and artist for 1 point each followed by 10 multiple choice questions. These three rounds are repeated twice. Â The last round is more difficult with 5 general knowledge questions worth 2 points and a bonus question worth an extra 5 points for the closest answer. At the start of the quiz participants pick up an image sheet consisting of 10 images, including maps (geography), products, films, celebrities, album covers, flags, brands, etc that your team can work on until the end of the quiz.

It's not an easy quiz, but it is lots of fun and the pub offers prizes to the three teams with the most points at the end of the night.

There is lots of time at the start and between rounds to chat, drink and order food. The quiz is free to play (you're not required to purchase food or drinks) so the evening can be as inexpensive as you choose to make it.
